  <!-- INTRO -->
  <div class="intro-section animate-on-scroll">
    <div class="section-label">Introduction</div>
    <p class="intro-lead">Most Americans believe they've handled their estate planning. <strong>Most of them are wrong.</strong></p>
    <p class="intro-body">Having a will doesn't mean your estate is protected. In fact, it's often the people who think they've "checked the box" who are most exposed — because they made decisions years ago that no longer reflect their situation, their assets, or the law.</p>
    <p class="intro-body">This report identifies the seven most common estate planning gaps we see in Americans aged 55–75. These aren't rare edge cases. They affect the majority of retirees — including those with substantial assets, good intentions, and even prior professional guidance.</p>

    <div class="alert-box">
      <div class="alert-icon">⚠</div>
      <div class="alert-text">The consequences of these gaps are not abstract. They mean <strong>probate courts deciding who gets your assets</strong>, families torn apart by legal disputes, decades of savings consumed by avoidable costs — and dying wishes that never get carried out.</div>
    </div>

    <p class="intro-body">Read this report with your family in mind. At the end, you'll find a simple checklist and a path forward that doesn't require a law degree — just the right guidance.</p>
  </div>

