  <!-- GAP 1 -->
  <div class="gap-section animate-on-scroll" id="gap1">
    <div class="gap-header">
      <div class="gap-number">01</div>
      <div class="gap-title-block">
        <div class="gap-category">Document Validity</div>
        <h2 class="gap-title">The Will Problem</h2>
        <div class="gap-severity critical">Critical Gap</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="gap-body">Most Americans who have a will believe they've done their estate planning duty. But a will is not a static document — it's a legal instrument that must evolve with your life. A will drafted when your children were young, when you lived in a different state, or when your net worth was a fraction of what it is today may be legally valid and practically useless at the same time.</p>

    <p class="gap-body">The most dangerous will is the one that exists but hasn't been reviewed in over five years. Life changes — divorces, births, deaths, new assets, new debts, changed relationships — can render your carefully planned document obsolete without voiding it. The court will still follow it, even when its instructions no longer reflect your wishes.</p>

    <div class="stat-callout">
      <div class="stat-big">57%</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">of American adults do not have a will — and of those who do, fewer than half have reviewed it in the past five years. A ten-year-old will is not estate planning. It's a liability.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="what-happens-box">
      <div class="what-happens-title">What happens without an updated will</div>
      <ul class="what-happens-list">
        <li>Your state decides who inherits — using intestacy laws that may not align with your wishes</li>
        <li>Former spouses, estranged relatives, or unintended parties may receive assets</li>
        <li>Minor children may have their inheritance managed by a court-appointed guardian you didn't choose</li>
        <li>Business interests, real estate, and financial accounts enter a slow, public, expensive probate process</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study">
      <div class="case-study-label">Illustrative Case — Composite Example</div>
      <p class="case-study-text">A retired engineer passed away with a will he'd written in 2009. He'd since remarried, moved from Texas to Florida, and sold a business. His will referenced accounts that no longer existed and left his estate to his first wife — because he'd never updated it after the divorce. The resulting legal battle consumed <strong>$180,000 in legal fees</strong> and took 3 years to resolve. His second wife received significantly less than he intended.</p>
      <div class="case-study-source">Names and identifying details changed. Composite of documented probate cases.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- GAP 2 -->
  <div class="gap-section animate-on-scroll" id="gap2">
    <div class="gap-header">
      <div class="gap-number">02</div>
      <div class="gap-title-block">
        <div class="gap-category">Asset Protection</div>
        <h2 class="gap-title">No Trust Structure</h2>
        <div class="gap-severity critical">Critical Gap</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="gap-body">A will tells the court what you want. A trust does it automatically, privately, and without a courthouse. The difference isn't legal semantics — it's tens of thousands of dollars, months of delay, and whether your family's financial affairs become public record.</p>

    <p class="gap-body">Probate — the court-supervised process of settling an estate through a will — is expensive, slow, and public. Attorney fees alone typically range from 2–5% of the gross estate. On a $600,000 estate, that's up to $30,000 gone before a single dollar reaches your family. A revocable living trust bypasses probate entirely, distributing assets to your beneficiaries according to your instructions — often within weeks rather than months or years.</p>

    <div class="stat-callout">
      <div class="stat-big">$30K</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">Average probate cost on a $600,000 estate when attorney fees, court costs, and administrative expenses are combined — all avoidable with a properly structured trust.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="what-happens-box">
      <div class="what-happens-title">Without a trust, your estate faces</div>
      <ul class="what-happens-list">
        <li>Public probate proceedings — your assets, debts, and beneficiaries become court record, accessible to anyone</li>
        <li>Mandatory delays of 9–24 months before assets can be distributed, regardless of family need</li>
        <li>Attorney and court fees typically consuming 3–7% of the gross estate value</li>
        <li>No mechanism to manage assets if you become incapacitated before death</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study">
      <div class="case-study-label">Illustrative Case — Composite Example</div>
      <p class="case-study-text">A retired schoolteacher with a $450,000 home and $280,000 in IRAs passed away with only a will in place. Her estate entered probate for <strong>14 months</strong>. Her two adult children — who needed access to funds to cover the mortgage during the process — were unable to access assets. Final legal and court costs totaled <strong>$38,000</strong>. A revocable living trust costing $2,500 to establish would have eliminated the entire process.</p>
      <div class="case-study-source">Names and identifying details changed. Composite of documented probate cases.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- GAP 3 -->
  <div class="gap-section animate-on-scroll" id="gap3">
    <div class="gap-header">
      <div class="gap-number">03</div>
      <div class="gap-title-block">
        <div class="gap-category">Account Titling</div>
        <h2 class="gap-title">Beneficiary Designation Errors</h2>
        <div class="gap-severity critical">Critical Gap</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="gap-body">Here is a fact that surprises most people: a beneficiary designation form overrides your will. It doesn't matter what your will says. Whoever is named on your IRA, 401(k), life insurance policy, or bank account will receive that asset — period. No court challenge, no family agreement, no last-minute change of heart can alter this.</p>

    <p class="gap-body">This makes outdated beneficiary designations one of the most dangerous and most common estate planning mistakes. People who named an ex-spouse in 1998 and never updated the form. People who named a parent who predeceased them, with no contingent beneficiary named. People who named their estate as beneficiary — triggering probate on assets specifically designed to avoid it.</p>

    <div class="stat-callout">
      <div class="stat-big">1 in 3</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">Americans with retirement accounts have beneficiary designations that are outdated, incorrect, or missing entirely — according to estate planning attorneys surveyed by the American College of Trust and Estate Counsel.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="what-happens-box">
      <div class="what-happens-title">Common beneficiary designation errors</div>
      <ul class="what-happens-list">
        <li>Ex-spouse named and never removed — they receive the asset regardless of divorce decree</li>
        <li>Deceased parent or sibling named with no contingent beneficiary — asset goes to probate</li>
        <li>Minor children named directly — a court-appointed guardian will control funds until age 18</li>
        <li>"My estate" named as beneficiary — eliminates the account's probate-avoidance benefit entirely</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- GAP 4 -->
  <div class="gap-section animate-on-scroll" id="gap4">
    <div class="gap-header">
      <div class="gap-number">04</div>
      <div class="gap-title-block">
        <div class="gap-category">Incapacity Planning</div>
        <h2 class="gap-title">The Power of Attorney Gap</h2>
        <div class="gap-severity high">High Priority</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="gap-body">Estate planning isn't only about what happens when you die. It's also about what happens if you can't speak for yourself. A durable power of attorney designates someone you trust to manage your financial affairs — pay bills, manage investments, handle real estate transactions — if you become incapacitated due to illness, accident, or cognitive decline.</p>

    <p class="gap-body">Without one, your family faces a court-supervised guardianship or conservatorship proceeding — a costly, time-consuming legal process that puts a judge in charge of appointing someone to manage your affairs. Even if your family unanimously agrees on who should serve, the court process can take months and cost thousands of dollars. And it plays out publicly.</p>

    <div class="stat-callout">
      <div class="stat-big">70%</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">of people over 65 will require some period of long-term care or incapacity assistance. A durable power of attorney costs $200–$500 to establish. A guardianship proceeding costs $3,000–$10,000 and takes 6–12 months.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="what-happens-box">
      <div class="what-happens-title">Without a durable power of attorney</div>
      <ul class="what-happens-list">
        <li>A court — not your family — decides who manages your finances</li>
        <li>Bills go unpaid, investments go unmanaged, and real estate decisions stall during proceedings</li>
        <li>The process takes months and costs thousands, draining the estate you're trying to protect</li>
        <li>Ongoing court oversight and reporting requirements persist for as long as you remain incapacitated</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- GAP 5 -->
  <div class="gap-section animate-on-scroll" id="gap5">
    <div class="gap-header">
      <div class="gap-number">05</div>
      <div class="gap-title-block">
        <div class="gap-category">Medical Planning</div>
        <h2 class="gap-title">No Healthcare Directive</h2>
        <div class="gap-severity critical">Critical Gap</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="gap-body">A healthcare proxy (also called a healthcare power of attorney) designates someone to make medical decisions on your behalf if you're unable to make them yourself. A living will documents your wishes about end-of-life treatment, life support, resuscitation, and related decisions. Together, they form a healthcare directive — and without one, the consequences for your family can be devastating.</p>

    <p class="gap-body">When a patient arrives at a hospital without a healthcare directive and is unable to communicate, the hospital must follow state law — which often means defaulting to aggressive life-sustaining treatment regardless of what the patient would have wanted. Family members without legal authority to make decisions may be excluded from discussions entirely. And when family members disagree, disputes can end up in court.</p>

    <div class="stat-callout">
      <div class="stat-big">72%</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">of Americans say they have not documented their end-of-life care preferences — leaving those decisions to hospitals, state law, and family members who may disagree about what you would have wanted.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="what-happens-box">
      <div class="what-happens-title">Without a healthcare directive</div>
      <ul class="what-happens-list">
        <li>Doctors default to maximum intervention — regardless of quality-of-life considerations</li>
        <li>Family members may be legally excluded from medical decisions if not formally designated</li>
        <li>Disagreements among family members can result in court proceedings — while you're still alive</li>
        <li>Your values, preferences, and dignity are left entirely to chance</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- GAP 6 -->
  <div class="gap-section animate-on-scroll" id="gap6">
    <div class="gap-header">
      <div class="gap-number">06</div>
      <div class="gap-title-block">
        <div class="gap-category">Long-Term Care Planning</div>
        <h2 class="gap-title">Medicaid Exposure</h2>
        <div class="gap-severity high">High Priority</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="gap-body">Long-term care costs are one of the most underestimated threats to retirement assets. The average annual cost of a private nursing home room exceeds $100,000 per year. Medicare covers almost none of it beyond the first 100 days. Medicaid does — but only after you've spent down most of your assets to qualify.</p>

    <p class="gap-body">What most people don't know is that Medicaid looks back five years when evaluating asset transfers. If you gave money to your children, moved assets into certain trusts, or made other transfers in the five years before applying for Medicaid, those transactions can trigger penalties — periods of ineligibility during which you must pay out-of-pocket for care. With proper advance planning, much of this exposure can be significantly reduced or eliminated.</p>

    <div class="stat-callout">
      <div class="stat-big">$108K</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">Average annual cost of a private nursing home room in 2025. With an average stay of 2.5 years, a couple facing simultaneous care needs could see $500,000+ in expenses — most of it unplanned for.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="what-happens-box">
      <div class="what-happens-title">Without Medicaid planning</div>
      <ul class="what-happens-list">
        <li>Assets accumulated over a lifetime spent down to meet Medicaid eligibility thresholds</li>
        <li>Family home potentially subject to Medicaid estate recovery after death</li>
        <li>Transfers made within 5 years of application trigger costly penalty periods</li>
        <li>Spousal protections go unclaimed — leaving the community spouse financially exposed</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- GAP 7 -->
  <div class="gap-section animate-on-scroll" id="gap7">
    <div class="gap-header">
      <div class="gap-number">07</div>
      <div class="gap-title-block">
        <div class="gap-category">Insurance & Legacy</div>
        <h2 class="gap-title">Life Insurance Gaps</h2>
        <div class="gap-severity high">High Priority</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="gap-body">Life insurance is a foundational estate planning tool — but only when it's structured correctly. The wrong coverage type, wrong ownership structure, or wrong beneficiary designation can turn a significant policy into a tax liability, a probate asset, or a resource that never reaches the people you intended to protect.</p>

    <p class="gap-body">For estates approaching or exceeding federal estate tax thresholds, life insurance owned by the insured is included in the taxable estate — potentially pushing heirs into a 40% federal estate tax on the proceeds. An Irrevocable Life Insurance Trust (ILIT) removes the policy from the taxable estate, ensuring the full death benefit reaches beneficiaries tax-free. Additionally, many retirees hold term policies purchased decades ago that are expiring just as their need for coverage is greatest.</p>

    <div class="stat-callout">
      <div class="stat-big">40%</div>
      <div class="stat-desc">Federal estate tax rate applied to taxable estates above the exemption threshold ($13.99M in 2026 — but scheduled to revert to approximately $7M in 2026 when the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act sunsets). Life insurance structured incorrectly is fully taxable.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="what-happens-box">
      <div class="what-happens-title">Common life insurance structure errors</div>
      <ul class="what-happens-list">
        <li>Policy owned by the insured — proceeds included in taxable estate at death</li>
        <li>Term policy expiring with no permanent coverage in place to fund estate obligations</li>
        <li>Outdated beneficiary designations routing proceeds to unintended recipients</li>
        <li>No survivorship policy to fund estate tax liability for married couples with larger estates</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

